<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910729-0153</DOCNO><DOCID>910729-0153.</DOCID><HL>   Condominium Scam   Results in Conviction   In Massachusetts Case</HL><DATE>07/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><RE>FLORIDA (FL)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   BOSTON -- William W. Lilly, a condominium developer whowas arrested in December, was convicted of 26 counts of bankfraud in which, prosecutors said, he pocketed more than $9million.   In the trial in U.S. district court, the governmentcharged that Mr. Lilly, a Lynnfield, Mass., resident, haddirected buyers of condominiums at a project in Haverhill,Mass., to sign purchase agreements that misstated the amountof down payment they were making.</LP><TEXT>   According to the government, he then used the signedagreements to obtain a $7 million loan from First Mutual Bankfor Savings, which was closed last month. Subsequently, hesold the fraudulent condominium mortgages for $9 million toRoyal Palm Savings Association, a West Palm Beach, Fla.,institution that became insolvent and was placed inconservatorship in 1989. The government said that many of themortgages have gone into default.   Donald Glusgol, a Peabody, Mass., real estate salesman whowas arrested with Mr. Lilly, pleaded guilty to fraud chargesand was a government witness at Mr. Lilly's trial.   Richard Welch, the assistant U.S. attorney who prosecutedthe case, said that each fraud count carries a maximumpenalty of five years in jail and a $250,000 fine.</TEXT></DOC>